ate to be </span><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:line-through">other</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> grounds for suspecting that a miscarriage of justice may have occurred.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">UKMPA Comment:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The UKMPA is concerned as to the intended meaning of “a miscarriage of Justice”.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The sole goal of any post accident safety investigation (as compared with an investigation for prosecution purposes) is to determine contributory and root causes in order where possible to effect changes to procedures and designs so as to prevent a re-occurrence.  Any investigation conclusions are based on the facts available at the time of the investigation.  It sometimes happens that a significant time period passes (following an investigation closure) that another pertinent fact of the circumstances of the accident is revealed.  Such new facts can sometimes have a significant effect on the conclusions reached in the initial investigation.  Clearly, where such new evidence surfaces, it is right and proper under principles of natural justice that the investigation be re-opened regardless of the effect it may have on the earlier investigation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The UKMPA’s concern is that it is not clear that this argument will still apply if </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">clause  269.1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(a) is deleted as proposed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If however the interpretation of “a miscarriage of justice” includes these circumstances and is not only limited to cases of legal prosecution (where it has been deemed appropriate) post accident, then those concerns are allayed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Chairman,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">UKMPA.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>